04757nam a22006615i 9780674041578DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222006mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806740415787 a10.4159/97806740415782doi  a(DE-B1597)571859  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHM671 ǂb N87 2006eb 7aPHI0190002bisacsh04a320.0111 aNussbaum, Martha C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFrontiers of Justice :bDisability, Nationality, Species Membership /cMartha C. Nussbaum. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (512 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTanner lectures on human values : 3100tFrontmatter -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tCONTENTS -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Social Contracts and Three Unsolved Problems of Justice -- t2. Disabilities and the Social Contract -- t3. Capabilities and Disabilities -- t4. Mutual Advantage and Global Inequality: The Transnational Social Contract -- t5. Capabilities across National Boundaries -- t6. Beyond “Compassion and Humanity”: Justice for Nonhuman Animals -- t7. The Moral Sentiments and the Capabilities Approach -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTheories of social justice are necessarily abstract, reaching beyond the particular and the immediate to the general and the timeless. Yet such theories, addressing the world and its problems, must respond to the real and changing dilemmas of the day. A brilliant work of practical philosophy, Frontiers of Justice is dedicated to this proposition. Taking up three urgent problems of social justice neglected by current theories and thus harder to tackle in practical terms and everyday life, Martha Nussbaum seeks a theory of social justice that can guide us to a richer, more responsive approach to social cooperation. The idea of the social contract—especially as developed in the work of John Rawls—is one of the most powerful approaches to social justice in the Western tradition. But as Nussbaum demonstrates, even Rawls’s theory, suggesting a contract for mutual advantage among approximate equals, cannot address questions of social justice posed by unequal parties. How, for instance, can we extend the equal rights of citizenship—education, health care, political rights and liberties—to those with physical and mental disabilities? How can we extend justice and dignified life conditions to all citizens of the world? And how, finally, can we bring our treatment of nonhuman animals into our notions of social justice? Exploring the limitations of the social contract in these three areas, Nussbaum devises an alternative theory based on the idea of “capabilities.” She helps us to think more clearly about the purposes of political cooperation and the nature of political principles—and to look to a future of greater justice for all.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)z978311075606708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311044220540uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674041578zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674041578423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674041578/original  a978-3-11-044220-5  Harvard University Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-075606-7  HUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013 (Canada)b2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL